_BtQqH">The disease once guaranteed an early death—but a new treatment has given many patients a chance to live decades longer than expected. What do they do now?</p></div><div class="ArticleHero_byline__iFT6A ArticleHero_twoColByline__VhWQ_"><div class="ArticleBylines_root__IBR5V ArticleBylines_twoCol__rmKE3"><address id="byline">By <a class="ArticleBylines_link__kNP4C" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/author/sarah-zhang/" data-action="click author - byline" data-label="https://www.theatlantic.com/author/sarah-zhang/" data-event-element="author" data-flatplan-author-link="true">Sarah Zhang</a><div>Photographs by Fumi Nagasaka</div></address></div></div></div><div class="ArticleLeadArt_root__nRSLU ArticleLeadArt_twoCol__XedW5"><figure class="ArticleLeadFigure_root__Bj81R"><div class="ArticleLeadFigure_media__R1npW" data-flatplan-lead_figure_media="true"><picture><img alt="photo of red-haired woman with eyes closed wearing black jacket in sunlight with mountain and blue sky in background" class="Image_root__XxsOp ArticleLeadArt_image__HZS4B" sizes="(min-width: 1440px) 656px, (min-width:1024px) calc(50vw - 64px), (min-width: 768px) calc(50vw - 48px), (min-width: 375px) calc(100vw - 103px), (min-width: 320px) calc(100vw - 64px), calc(100vw - 48px)" srcSet="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/1Eabd7ub5HPB07q-0meMaIXuxOo=/101x1:2500x3000/296x370/media/img/2024/03/05/Zhang_1/original.png 296w, https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/T9jDnQy6bEpz7WT0e3MRNGbgtBc=/101x1:2500x3000/311x389/media/img/2024/03/05/Zhang_1/original.png 311w, https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/2r_j3cV3xUUJtJmii-tUSn-8SJo=/101x1:2500x3000/592x740/media/img/2024/03/05/Zhang_1/original.png 592w, https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/TWuPX5yogr9dje8-unFLa2Pa4Cg=/101x1:2500x3000/622x778/media/img/2024/03/05/Zhang_1/original.png 622w, https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/skuI-ulo3PaX1C1Me8n3B5YizaU=/101x1:2500x3000/665x831/media/img/2024/03/05/Zhang_1/original.png 665w, https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/Ur6nBwIDxRP55BENwPLJDxcFY-U=/101x1:2500x3000/960x1200/media/img/2024/03/05/Zhang_1/original.png 960w, https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/pAWc6dPZNFskYYqf2YPO-0xpnSQ=/101x1:2500x3000/1330x1663/media/img/2024/03/05/Zhang_1/original.png 1330w" src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/N3MCH5VhgILdOXcF7cTMUSQ2zSE=/101x1:2500x3000/648x810/media/img/2024/03/05/Zhang_1/original.png" id="article-lead-image" width="648" height="810"/></picture></div><figcaption class="ArticleLeadFigure_caption__Byu7W ArticleLeadFigure_twoColCaption__WSIXu" data-flatplan-lead_figure_caption="true"><span>Before she started taking Trikafta, in 2019, Jenny Livingston hoped more than anything to survive long enough to see her daughter graduate from high school.</span></figcaption></figure></div></div><div class="ArticleHero_articleUtilityBar__JbQFj"><div class="ArticleHero_timestamp__bKhcB"><time class="ArticleTimestamp_root__b3bL6" dateTime="2024-03-07T12:00:00Z" data-flatplan-timestamp="true">March 7, 2024</time></div><div class="ArticleHero_articleUtilityBarTools__ZHw8s"><div class="ArticleShare_root__Mq0RB"><button class="ArticleShare_text__oQKBy ArticleShare_shareButton__X0cIe" aria-haspopup="true" aria-controls=":Rp2qoomm:" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Open Share Menu" data-action="click share - expand" data-event-verb="shared" data-event-element="share dropdown">Share<svg width="15" height="15" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="ArticleShare_shareIcon__G4iq1"><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M7.335.272a.25.25 0 01.337 0l4.623 4.204a.25.25 0 01.017.353l-.336.37a.25.25 0 01-.353.016L8.004 1.926v7.9a.25.25 0 01-.25.25h-.5a.25.25 0 01-.25-.25V1.924l-3.62 3.291a.25.25 0 01-.353-.016l-.336-.37a.25.25 0 01.016-.353L7.335.272zM.5 7.545a.25.25 0 00-.25.25v6.75c0 .138.112.25.25.25h14a.25.25 0 00.25-.25v-6.75a.25.25 0 00-.25-.25H14a.25.25 0 00-.25.25v6H1.25v-6a.25.25 0 00-.25-.25H.5z" fill="#000"></path></svg></button></div><button class="ArticleSave_text__PMSa1 Ar